The Ukrainian Parliament today refused to accept the request to abolish the paragraphs on the basis of which the opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been condemned as part of a revision of the Criminal Code.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the Minister of Foreign Affairs, was rejected by the Members at the second reading of the request for the reduction of the penalties for economic offences.
In October, Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the conclusion of a supposedly negative contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet in force, and in December the appeal of the convicted is to be negotiated in court.
Tymoshenko himself denies the judgment as a political revenge of the regime and in the West the trial caused the suspicion of the court's premonition.
The request to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was sentenced to leave the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 Members.
226 votes would have been necessary for it to be adopted.
