V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The original careless journey is made by a series of completely avoidable, dilttantian errors for routine travel to the early shift.
Although it was possible to fulfil the ambitions to a large extent, what is the point of doing this if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the shop tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to move the game series "Need for Speed" back to a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he did not seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about how the fit passages in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are already used to at NFS, in the end, much is different from what you expected.
Sure - it is potentially quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is reduced by some unnecessary errors that have been present in this series for more or less years.
So it is no longer a mistake, but rather a sign of a, in principle, unintelligible sincerity of the game developers.
The adventure begins very well.
For the first time, one is introduced into history, whose main character Jack has certain problems of personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole range of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is carried out on a different route and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don't have the impression that game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments are still very nice to see, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the journey through the desert, through autumn landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape is very pleasant visually.
Every now and then, untypical elements bring a little variety into the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts the view.
In the mountains, in turn, you have to be very careful not to be spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in a row.
Just a few, but they're enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to pick up (classic race against the stop clock), then you expect another personal duel with a single opponent.
And that's what the police want to mess up the whole thing.
One new thing is passages where Jack leaves the car.
This is more about certain interactive animations where Jack is fleeing from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right time.
So nothing complicated.
It is, however, surprising that there are much less such passages in the game than one would expect (in concrete terms only three).
In the end, this is more to the advantage, because this element has at least no chance of getting boring - it is in the context of the above mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model is on the feet of the previous parts.
This means, from a current point of view, that it does not tear out trees, on the other hand, it could not be said that it is bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But the local driving model is still well suited to an action-loaded race, even though it is possible to find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in order.
Real problems only show up after some time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not entirely O.K.
There is little to expect from a game of this kind that it will calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you don't have any idea how the car is doing in the past, it's obviously not all right.
Typical example: When you overtake or get in front of the car you "strip" the other car in some places only easily, but in other, almost identical situation you get into the loop and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the car is about to go to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter any more, it's all annoying.
The restarts are so solved: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then you throw the game back to the last point of reference of the track.
Only - in every race you only have five restarts.
When they're exhausted, everything goes from the front.
So the restarts are more of a tool, in case something doesn't succeed, but you don't want to rely on it.
Sometimes, however, the reboot does not even help, there is nothing other than to learn the critical section from the head.
Extremely unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, have to be carried through in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
Otherwise, you always meet "civilian" cars at the appropriate place in the same configuration, whether you are the first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when you see that the opponent comes by before a playing two coming cars, but until you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The competitors have other advantages.
In the whole game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent in the same place and again here without regard to the time.
This is the most crazy thing to do at the end of the game on the long bridge that happens in the opposite direction.
The adversary has to get you out of here, obviously.
And if he's already in front of you, he'll take a look at you, so you can start driving your own car in a few times.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so clear that it quickly saves you the joy of the game.
And that is a pity, because despite a simpler driving model, the game is generally quite entertaining and sometimes also so active that you almost don't know where the head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "fault" is - the concept of fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car in the course of the races.
You must not miss the gas stations on the line, because here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight motorways and exotic super-sports cars for the technical trips, for example on the serpentine in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game history also goes the task mode (challenges) - that is, the races in the individual locations that you know from history.
There are not only medals here, but also points of experience for their own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and history.
To get to the higher driver level, different items must be opened up: from the car to the background for the profile.
This is connected to the online function Autolog, which, among other things, compares its own results with those of other players and also ensures further collective functions.
One of another incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you get to a subway tunnel (because of me) by car, where you ride on the tracks in the dark (because of me).
On the Tacho see numbers between 150 and 200 km / h (for my part), but there comes a subway from the back and a uncompromising road to scrap.
In our editorial work, we are going to argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the players or whether the authors think we're so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and even brilliant here and there.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the frequency of the image is getting slower and sometimes rather dramatic.
This, however, concerns, in particular, accidents involving a greater number of persons, where a continuous FPS does not benefit you anyway.
The sound is so far O.K. and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
A soundtrack a lá "of everyone" was created in an effort to address a wide scale as only possible, but who is buying such a game because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are more mixed.
If the game were not undermined by the absolutely unnecessary errors mentioned above, we could have claimed with the chest tone that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's kind of how the game works.
A great pleasure in itself, but one should be prepared to see these mistakes stabbing into your eyes with the power of airport headlights.
