Travel price trends since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five state travel agencies approved in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies sold only to the socialist East Bloc countries, and in the West only the chosen were allowed at that time.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was also possible to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
At that time the travel agencies also offered to travel to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel office.
This was not the way things were going.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for an exit to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely replaceable currency, so it would have been impossible to obtain the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a journey to the West without a foreign exchange agreement.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues until today.
The round revolution of 1989 followed a journey revolution of the Czechs on their feet.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries all over the world last year.
A huge paradox, which is no longer known today, is the fact that it was not possible to travel to the most popular country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange obligation was lifted to the neighbouring Western European countries, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their journeys to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
The Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in the park when they were travelling to Paris, because who would have had the money to stay in the hotel or in a guesthouse at that time.
A typical feature of Czech travel abroad was then a trunk filled with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely replaceable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of living and the average salaries thus also increased, which in 1997 led to another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies started to prepare regular travel through charter flights after 1997, thus allowing flights to negotiate volume discounts to be unbelievably reduced in comparison to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czech Republic, with the exception of the United States, already had a deficit in payments with all the highly developed countries in the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-assembled" travel was in 2000 when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was made - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying in far-away sunny countries every year; this year, 12 exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Tsd Czechs travel every year in exotic countries!
Another important moment in the era, which marked our "post-revolutionary" development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czech authorities spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 Tsd per capita on a single holiday stay, including the cost of the holiday place.
