Walls have eyes: How researchers watch you on Facebook
Before he became a new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who has confessed to having committed an ammo in Norway in July, where 77 people were killed, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he has spent a lot of time before his attack in front of his computer and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on the sides of social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
This is easy - you only have to log in on Facebook.
"We have noted that it was not difficult to come to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the main author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebooks hiding personal data is so encyclopaedic, Bartlett says that the researchers simply have to use the advertising tool of the site to determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - just as the marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of the extreme right across Europe and then visited them with Adds, but instead of being linked to a new band or a new diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking for their educational status, their attitude to violence and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question more than 10,000 supporters of 14 very right parties in 11 European countries - without even having to leave their office once.
"It's a rather new research method," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online supporters of the right-wing extreme groups are usually young, male and are angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens."
