Climate distortions have slowed the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is a government, unemployment and undeclared work increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investment went down and the economy stagnated.
In 2011, the economic history of Sinaloas will remain in mind. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who called himself the initiator of change and raised great hopes of economic growth, is the government. However, due to the climatic tides, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators have deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February did not only lead to millions of losses in agriculture, but also to close limits on the growth of the state economy and in the first quarter of the year caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6%. This is mainly due to the historical reduction in agricultural development by 31.16%, which has had a significant impact on other sectors of the economy.
According to a report by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustainable (d. Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frost, 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% were partly destroyed.
The decline in economic activity up to November has led to a continuous increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, as from January to March, 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloas had no employment, which is 4.53% of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate increased to 5.28% and from July to 6.19%, resulting in 74 000 unemployed people in Sinaloa, which is 18 969 people more than in the first quarter.
Reduced liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is based on several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented that the policy of the public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity on the market as a result of the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because it is not easy for those who have to accumulate the dollar to make it work for themselves, to invest it or to use it for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen, on the one hand, due to the problems of entry and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there too, and these people are staying here and looking for work, which will increase unemployment," he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if the high proportion of undeclared work is taken into account, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38% of those employed in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
The low wages, the lowest in the whole of Mexico, come from unemployment and undeclared work, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Care in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September, much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADI
In addition to the reduction of economic activity and growing unemployment, the largest fall in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to the Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI was 630 597 dollars from January to June, which corresponds to an 87.74 percent blow compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development), in turn, has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
In the light of the economic crisis, the national government requested a loan of 3 000 000 million pesos to be invested in the 18 municipalities of the country in July at the National Congress, but no positive effects of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country were found by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government Mario López Valdé made it clear that the government was unable to do so.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of the Manufacturing Industry in Mexico) said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the national government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. It must be worked hard to regain the terrain lost this year and we must make a double effort in 2012. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the well-agreed government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important effects is a slow economy that is not sufficiently moving to create an economic dynamic that could create an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will close the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican business association) in Sinaloa, said that the state must be encouraged to become more dynamic productive.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources of Sinaloas," he said.
There's a lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that would guide the government's efforts in a better way.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
