In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Elektoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, has reminded that, just last November, the election office had adopted a number of rules for the harmonisation of local rules with the reforms of the states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, his electoral law, or his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they had not entered into force in this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the Public Prosecutor's Office within the time limits set for it, with the argument that he had no objection to it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional action brought by the local legislature and considered the voice of the State Commissioner on the constitutional reforms to be "invalid and illegal," as it does not have the right to "decide" or to veto it. "
María de los Ángeles Llanderal, in an interview on the possibility of the individual count of votes, stated that, thanks to the adoption of the directives by the Consejo General del IEM, there is now the possibility that the local electoral authority may count the voting papers in part or in part.
For example, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may not be counted in part. The results in the minutes are not in agreement; the minutes on the count and calculation of votes are not in fact available or it is not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or changes in the minutes.
In addition, the total number of the full-completed ballot cards may be given if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the one who is in second place, which is equal or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an express request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the candidates mentioned.
The vote may also be taken as a whole if, after the normal calculation has been completed, it is found that the difference between the expected winner and the candidate in second place is equal or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the election packages that have been subject to a partial count would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is just under 0.16%, although the votes of 129 of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
