Who were you influenced by as a bassist?
Of so many +
One of the first to come up with me is Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I can talk about the bassist I like all afternoon.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the ground alive, even though it is no longer a fashion appearance?
I don't think we all feel very connected to the word "grunge."
When I think about it, I think of the bands that I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think it's great, because it's worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney make better music now than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now she is more positive.
Why?
This is interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that could seem a little light-ready, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Break, which are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive in them.
The two of them came to me when I heard Ed playing them, they're very dark songs.
I think if you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - for example, if you lose a family member or a friend - it will affect your artistic creation and your music and these two songs clearly represent this for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
