MSS announces a research protocol to find the gene for obesity
The Social Insurance Institute of Mexico is the head of a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and young people, which is supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institute of Mexico) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth," with which the genetic markers are to be found in conjunction with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, said that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, food specialists and social workers was established.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinistav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports sites of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are carried out every Saturday from 8: 00.
He stressed that the investigation began at the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of México) and was continued in the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México) since October 8.
When the target of 500 to 600 people is reached, the study will be continued at the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and completed on the site of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He said that the aim of the study was to identify the factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors of Mexican children and young people to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the global day of diabetes, he said that three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 should be able to fill out food-related questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and their family disease in order to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or renal failure.
It also stated that on the above-mentioned Saturdays, the test subjects (weight, size, waist size) were measured, their blood pressure controlled and blood levels such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (an attempt to identify genes related to child obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out in the light of the concern of health care staff about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in almost six years the proportion of fat-bearing boys had increased by 77% and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. The overweight had also increased dramatically," said IMSS's specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the people of Mexico was different from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average Mexican was 65% Indian-American, 30% European and 5% African, which was reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
