The new gas pipeline will provide 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year through a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length, which connects the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, to Western Europe.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - equivalent to the French total consumption - will be completed at the end of 2012.
And you already make the possibility of building a third line sound on your own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building is like a victory.
The project was very controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The North Stream pipeline will allow direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any road run by third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on the land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little bit of their power: it is now more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, the most committed in the debate, was not to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is extremely sensitive politically.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, is at the expense of a European energy degeneration, as the project has made a break between Western and Eastern Europeans.
Russia has in almost five years completed its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries with strong gas consumption and their gas supplies.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," said François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out in what degree the large gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All of this explains the wide smile of the Gazprom managers in Lubmin, who are numerous, as regards the gas transmission.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line is made up of steel with a concrete encapsulation, which it is intended to protect from ship anchors.
It rests on the sea floor, about 200 m deep.
In the construction of the mine fields from the Second World War, it was necessary to avoid.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed for the sake of caution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for the North Stream company.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project leaders have taken away from it, because Sweden was not in a position to see a Russian state society on a permanent basis at the level of its coasts.
"In the case of a ovary, we close the gas flow in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the case of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline is then released into the air.
However, this case is considered to be unlikely by the constructors, as the weld seam was estimated to be resistant to one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of gas transmission is ensured by both an underwater robot controlled for external observation by a seagoing vessel and by a device circulating inside the gas transmission.
It has the form of a cigar, measures a meter in diameter, is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on any deformations of the metal on its arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without even having to be subjected to the least repair.
The gas circulation is easily guaranteed by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entry point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have united their forces to achieve this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The German companies E. ON and BASF are also classified here (15.5% each), as are the Dutch Gas Union and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a business community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug in Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented this company the entire capacity of its gas transport, on an extendable 20-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transport of gas is," said Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas pipeline was covered by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amount was 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are sure to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone is at risk of liability.
The gas pipeline is shown by a sandy, pine-wooded coastline at Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5-metre-high valves form the gas exit path.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is passed on to the German gas pipelines.
